Assignment 1

PROBLEM 1:

Problem 1 involves real estate sales across the five boroughs of New York City. I started by loading the datasets for the Bronx, Brooklyn, Manhattan, Queens, and Staten Island into R.

I loaded the sales data for each borough, standardized the column names, and combined the datasets by adding a column to identify the borough.

I formatted the sale dates, handled missing values by removing columns like ease.ment while retaining useful ones, converted relevant columns to numeric types, and filtered out entries with zero or missing sale prices.

I focused on specific residential building categories, including one-, two-, and three-family homes, coops, and condos, by creating a subset called nyc_residential and added sale.month and sale.year columns for temporal analysis.

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

Visualizing Sale Prices

Histogram of Sale Prices:

Plotted sale prices across different building categories.

Observation: The distribution was right-skewed, with most properties sold at lower prices and fewer high-priced sales.

Boxplots by Borough:

Created boxplots to compare sale prices across boroughs.

Observation: Manhattan stood out with higher median and mean sale prices, indicating a more expensive real estate market.

Sale Prices Over Time

Scatter Plot:

Plotted sale prices over the sale date, color-coded by borough.

Observation: There wasnt a distinct trend over time, but Manhattan consistently showed higher sale prices.

Statistical Summary

I calculated summary statistics grouping by building category and borough:

  • Count: Number of sales in each group.

  • Mean and Median Sale Price: Average and middle value sale prices.

  • Standard Deviation: Variability within each group

Key Findings:

  • Manhattan: Dominated in terms of higher sale prices across all categories. Reflects the premium real estate market in this borough.
  • Staten Island and the Bronx: Had lower average sale prices, indicating more affordable housing options.

Conclusions and Insights

Analyzing the NYC real estate data provided several insights:

  • Market Variations: Theres a significant disparity in property values between Manhattan and the outer boroughs.

  • Property Types: Single-family homes are more prevalent in Staten Island and Queens, while Manhattan has more coops and condos.

  • Investment Opportunities: Investors might find lucrative opportunities in Manhattan for high-end properties.

  • Affordable housing projects could focus on the Bronx and Staten Island.

PROBLEM 2:

Problem 2 involves simulated advertising data from the New York Times homepage over three days. The datasets (nyt1.csv, nyt2.csv, nyt3.csv) represent user interactions with ads, including age, gender, ad impressions, clicks, and login status for each user.

Ive prepared the data by creating age groups for demographic analysis, to allow for grouping and comparing user behavior across different life stages.

Ive converted numerical codes like gender and login status to descriptive labels, calculated click-through rates, and segmented users based on click behavior to analyze engagement patterns.

Exploratory Data Analysis

Comparing User Segments

<20-Year-Old Males vs.Females

Impressions

Observation: Both genders had similar distributions, but males showed a slightly higher median.

CTR

Observation: Males under 20 had a marginally higher CTR than females.
